@node main "Tame Shell Master"

@{fg highlight}@{bg text}

Tame Shell Master

@{fg shine}
Copyright 1998/99@{bg background}@{fg text}	J—rg van de Loo
		H—vel 15
		47559 Kranenburg

		Germany


A brief introduction...


Tame  Shell  Master  (called short TSM) is a program, which will allow you to drag one or more icons per time
from  your  workbench  desk  into  a  CLI  or  Shell-window  where  the  filename  of  the icon or icons will be
displayed as normal text-characters.

The only thing you have to do is to call TSM from the Shell, which should support drag and drop.

Enter at the appearing prompt TSM and hit the RETURN-key.

1> TSM [RETURN]
1>

TSM  will  not print any message onscreen, it allows you only to drag an icon from the workbench desk into a
Shell-window  where  you  can  release  it.  If  TSM  is  running,  the  filename  of the icon is shown as if you
entered its filename directly. If not, nothing happens.

TSM  is  a  fix-in-place  that adds drag-and-drop to your Shell. It's mainly written for advantage users of the
Amiga-Operating-System  (Amiga-OS)  because  those folks will use a Shell as often as the Workbench and
of course a Shell is more flexible than a Workbench.

TSM  has  been  written in approximately 25 hours where I spent the most time to see where I have to hook up
the  Amiga-Disk-Operating-System  (Amiga-DOS)  without  disturbing  it.  Since  the  Amiga-DOS manual is
very  rare  at backgrounds, I had to try a few ways where a lot end up in a disaster (totally system crash) until
I found out the right one.

If  you  take  a  look  at  the  source-code  you never imagine why it took so long to write TSM, it appears all
simple and easy. But without fundamental information it's a very hard task to do.


@{fg text}@{bg highlight}Requirements@{bg background}@{fg text}
TSM  requires  very  less  memory  (less  than 5 Kbytes, including stack) and at least Kickstart 2.0 (V36). The
workbench desk must not be necessarily opened, but - it should, otherwise TSM cannot do any work.


@{fg text}@{bg highlight}Background@{bg background}@{fg text}
TSM  will  not  patch  any  system-function,  it will talk to the DOS and vice versa via packets, thus it will not
busy   wait!   TSM  will  start  an  independent  background  process  with  a  normal  task  priority.  TSM  will
auto-detach from the process-environment from where it has been launched.
You may use the Resident command to hold TSM resident in memory where it requires only 2 Kbytes.
When  it  is resident it will also auto-detach from the Shell process (one of the few programs ever programmed
for  the  Amiga  that  will  support  it)  even  it is 100 percent system-conform programmed in 68k assembler to
make it REALLY re-entrant.


@{fg text}@{bg highlight}A Hint@{bg background}@{fg text}
Edit  the  Shell-Start-up  file to make TSM available for any Shell-process you will use, i.e. enter somewhere
in the Shell-Startup-file "TSM". That's all.


@{fg text}@{bg highlight}Usage@{bg background}@{fg text}
Usage  is  permitted  for any reasons (okay, not for criminal aims) by any persons so long no person make me
held  liable  for  any  possible  occurring  error.  It's  also allow to spread it on any cover disks or CDs or any
electronic net without written permission from the author.


@{fg text}@{bg highlight}Setbacks@{bg background}@{fg text}
In  some circumstances TSM does not allow the Shell-window to be closed. This occurs often in heavy (over)
loaded  systems and when some (alien) applications turn off the multitasking in this case. There is currently no
known way to avoid it.

Nevertheless,  to  shut  down  the  Shell-window  TSM  can  be  forced  to  quit  by sending a BREAK signal.
Unfortunately,   this  must  be  done  explicit  either  by  using  a  system-monitor  or  by  using  Commodores
BreakTask command that can be found within the NDUK package.

1> NDUK:Tools/BreakTask TSM

Note:  TSM  will use as task name its filename, so, if you've typed at the Shell-prompt "tsm" instead of "TSM",
the task name is "tsm"! This is important to know if you use the BreakTask command!



                      TSM Copyright 1998 ONIX
                      TSM is "Freeware"




@{fg text}@{bg highlight}History@{bg background}@{fg text}
13.09.1998 Version 1.0
Initial version, works.

04.10.1998 Version 1.1
Works  fine  until  the  Rexx-server  quits  a  client. With the Rexx-client TSM was gone, too. Now dp_Arg2 is
checked for zero indicating the user really want to close the Shell-window.

TSM  did  not allow shutting down console window when the task priority of the console task and TSM differ -
the  mistake  that  I've  made  was  to check within the main-routine the message type. But it could be that the
message  had  been already freed from memory - invalid memory access and therewith an unreliable result of
the  message  parsing. Now it is really non-important which priorities TSM and the console task own because
from within the console task TSM will get a break signal what ever works.

25.10.1998
File size shortened. No increased version number.

12.12.1998 Version 1.2
The  only  things  that indicates that a 'Shell-window' should be closed I know so far is that the dp_Type field
is  set  to  ACTION_END  and  dp_Res1  to  minus  one.  Now  TSM  cares about it - no longer only a lonely
checking of dp_Arg2.
TSM¿  will  fire  up  TSMý  with  a  task priority that is one less tall than the one of the Shell-task, which TSMý
utilizes.

13.11.1999
Deals now also with a CLI/Shell found on a Workbench 1.2 / 1.3 disk. No increased version number.



